              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">Etiquette in Star Wars CCG</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a3.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2586"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2586"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=1524">chris "wampa hunter" benson</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 1524 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">This Article takes a look your role as a Star Wars CCG and how you should conduct yourself in tourneys or just the casual game. This should be expected of each and every player.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">I&#146;ll take a look at first, what to do the night before a tourney and then follow through the day of the tourney. Most of this is common sense, but since people are still guilty of some of the things that I mention  below, It needs to be said again!<br>
<br>
NIGHT BEFORE<br>
<br>
 Your decks should be already to go at this point. Leaving it to the last moment will lead to poor choices for your card slots and most likely lost games. Get to bed at a reasonable hour, so your fresh for the big day.<br>
<br>
DAY OF<br>
<br>
 Be sure to have a plan on how to get the tourney all set up, give yourself plenty of time to have a shower and have breakfast. No one wants to play against a player with B.O. and looks like he/she has no self respect. (we&#146;re not Magic players after all!! =D ). Plan to be at the tourney at least 1/2 hour before kick off, this will give you time to trade or whatever. Have your Command Sheet filled out before the tourney starts.<br>
<br>
DURING THE TOURNEY<br>
<br>
 After your pairings are called out find a seat and introduce yourself to your opponate if you don&#146;t know him or her. Be friendly and open, don&#146;t put on your &quot;game face&quot;.  Sports players use this intimidate the other team, it has no place in Star Wars CCG . You&#146;ll only be taken as a snob.<br>
<br>
If your playing a new player, help him/her out by reminding them the phases of their turn if they forget, or helpful tips along the way.(ex. They forget to force drain, casually remind them they have forgotten something) For the experienced player, you know that most of time you could crush a newbie player&#146;s deck, But making it fun for the new player, he/she they will be back to play in more tourneys.<br>
<br>
 Be aware that some people might not know the rules as well as you do, so if someone is doing something wrong or illegal. Explain to them what they did wrong, if the problem persists call the TD.<br>
<br>
 Don&#146;t crowded around people playing their game. They have enough to worry about, with out having to feel that they are on centre stage.   <br>
<br>
 If your tourney is in a mall or some other public place, be prepared for people to stop by and ask questions. Look them in the eye and smile, and explain what the game is and what your all doing here. If they seem interested, have a few common decks (made up before hand) with a rule book to hand out. Most of the younger people will be thrilled that your giving away free cards!<br>
<br>
 If you&#146;re a highly ranked player don&#146;t feel that your better than the rest of the guys around you because you have a higher ranking.<br>
<br>
 Also if are beaten by a lower ranked player, please don&#146;t start telling your friends that you were cheated out the win or that if you had X card, the winner&#146;s deck would have fallen apart. all this does, is make the winner feel guilty for winning. The expenced player should congratulate the lower ranked player for the good game. You were beaten far and square, don&#146;t cry about it.<br>
<br>
AFTER THE TOURNEY<br>
<br>
 Be sure that everyone gets some sort of prize, especially the new players. I was hooked to Star Wars CCG when I went to my first tourney and lost nearly every game, but at the end I was given a Starter Pack. WOW!<br>
<br>
 Be sure to thank the store that supported the tourney and who ever ran the tourney. They work hard to make this game fun for everyone, it&#146;s the least you can do. Also offer to help clean up the chairs and tables and whatever trash is lying around<br>
<br>
Be sure to support the store that held the tourney. Buy a few packs or singles from them. This will reinforce the fact that having Star Wars CCG tourneys at their store is a good thing. Also it might help to offset any cost the tourney caused.<br>
<br>
<br>
LAST BUT NOT LEAST...<br>
It&#146;s a game, don&#146;t take it too seriously!!! =D<br>
<br>
<br>
Thanks for reading my article! I know I must of missed some etiquette rules, feel free to write a follow-up.  Hope you will use some of my suggestions!<br>
<br>
wampa hunter<br>
<br>
<br>
For those that are going to rate this article, please don&#146;t put &quot;No new info&quot; because I don&#146;t visit this site every day and have no idea what you have already read or what other people have wrote about.<br>
